editorialNotes.standard: We’ve played so many games that we feel like we could create our own—and now we can, all without coding classes or complex tutorials. With this ingenious educational app, it's easy to become a designer. Imagination rules as you build characters, worlds and stories for one-of-a-kind games meant to be saved, shared and—of course—played.

name: Little Kitten My Pet Kitty Cat

editorialNotes.standard: The moment we met wee kitty Crumbs in Little Kitten, we let out an audible “awww.” This adorable digital feline encourages children to play and explore, interacting with the lively toys and simple games in Crumbs’ room. We’re amazed by the cinematic animation, and appreciate the sleep timer that sends Crumbs to bed when our kids’ screen time is over.
editorialNotes.short: Embark on exciting adventures with your own kitty pal.

editorialNotes.standard: This debut app in Tinybop’s Digital Toys series lets kids create, test and put into action whatever they can imagine. Scientists-in-training can construct thousands of physics-driven robots—from lizards and wizards to dancers and doctors—using 100 different interchangeable parts, then test them in real-world scenarios. Experiment with motion, colour, sound and function, then for extra fun, make your robots dance. A kid-friendly multi-user system encourages budding creators of all ages to flex their imagination, then show off their robot masterpieces in a special showroom.
editorialNotes.short: Design and experiment with all types of robots.
Take virtual arts and crafts lessons from Dr Panda!
editorialNotes.tagline: Fun with virtual art and craft

editorialNotes.standard: Slide a shape into the correct hole—easy, right? It is, at first. But what makes Busy Shapes so clever is the way it gently gets more challenging, motivating little kids to find solutions to each puzzle through experimentation. From shape-changing to colour-mixing to hidden holes, we’re impressed with how the gameplay spurs out-of-the-box thinking, stimulating curious young minds.

ios.subtitle: Phonics Game to Learn to Read

editorialNotes.standard: Part digital toy and part planetary handbook, The Earth gives kids insight into the workings of our world in a way that’s delightfully intuitive and fun. From rockslides to earthquakes to erupting volcanoes, these artful interactive dioramas respond to tapping and swiping with results that are both whimsical and educational. An accompanying guide for parents and teachers delves into the technical science behind all these phenomena, but kids can explore, experiment, and absorb earthly knowledge at their own pace.
editorialNotes.short: Play with interactive models to understand our planet.

name: Jack and the Beanstalk Interactive Storybook

editorialNotes.standard: An utterly charming way to introduce young kids to music and animation, Loopimal is simple and powerful in a way that almost defies description. Kids arrange and rearrange tiles in sequences underneath a cute polar bear, octopus, and the like, triggering a series of musical tones mirrored by adorable dances from the animal gang. There are no goals and no consequences—just a safe place to learn, play, and laugh.

Interactive alphabet learning where words and letters come to life.

editorialNotes.standard: Ready to unleash your cartoon alter ego? CHOMP takes your face and sticks it on dozens of interactive animations, letting you instantly record the bizarre and hilarious results. Scenarios can turn you into a wacky superhero, a concert pianist, a panda—even water dripping from a tap. The beautiful, simple, feel-good illustrations make for the type of silly fun that guarantees laughter from all ages.
